1250–1310","1220–Female":"1220–Deceased","1315":"1315","1259":"1259","1224":"1224","1310":"1310","1210":"1210","1220":"1220","1240":"1240","1250":"1250","about 1220":"about 1220","1328":"1328","1317":"1317","1290":"1290","Hythe, Essex, England":"Essex, England","<, Hythe, Essex>, England":"Essex, England","Hythe, Kent, England":"Hythe, Kent, England","England, United Kingdom":"England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Layer","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Otto, Franz, Hans.","English: habitational name from any of the three places in Essex – Layer Breton, Layer de la Haye, and Layer Marney – all named from a river name, <i>Leire</i>, the name of a small stream, thought to be from a Celtic word meaning ‘mud’.","English: nickname or status name from Anglo-Norman French <i>le eyr</i> ‘the heir’. Compare   Ayer  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Ayer","meanings":["English and Scottish: from Middle English <i>eir</i>, <i>eyr</i> ‘heir’ (Anglo-Norman French <i>heyr</i>, Old French <i>(h)eir</i>, Latin <i>heres</i>). Forms such as <i>Richard le Heyer</i> were frequent in Middle English, denoting a man who was well known to be the heir to the main property in a particular locality, either one who had already inherited or one with great expectations.","English: from the Anglo-Norman French and Middle English personal name <i>Aier</i> (ancient Germanic <i>Agihari</i>).","English: variant of   Hair  ."]},{"name":"Layher","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Kurt.","German: variant of   Layer   4."]},{"name":"Lear","meanings":["English: nickname from Middle English <i>ler</i> ‘cheek, face, countenance, complexion’ (Old English <i>hlēor</i>), used adjectivally to mean ‘beautiful of face’.","English: variant of   Layer  .","Irish: shortened Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Mac Giolla Uidhir</b> ‘son of the swarthy lad’ or ‘son of the servant of <i>Odhar</i>’, a byname from <i>odhar</i> (genitive <i>uidhir</i>) ‘dun-colored’, ‘weatherbeaten’. Compare   McAleer  ."]}]},{"name":"Alice","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Originally a variant of   Adelaide  , representing an Old French spelling of a reduced form of Germanic <i>Adalheidis</i>. <i>Alice</i> and <i>Adelaide</i> were already regarded as distinct names in English during the medieval period. <i>Alice</i> enjoyed a surge of popularity in the 19th century and periods of favour ever since. It was the name of the central character of  Lewis Carroll's  Alice's Adventures in Wonderland (  1865 ) and Through the Looking Glass (  1872 ), who was based on his child friend  Alice Liddell , daughter of the Dean of Christ Church, Oxford."],"variants":[{"name":"Alys","meanings":["Variant spelling of   Alice ."]},{"name":"Alis","meanings":["equivalent of <b>Alice</b> ."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705188,"age":4,"year":"1224","julianDay":2168117,"title":"France Declares War on England","description":"France declared war on England as Louis VIII of France attacked Poitou and northern Gascony.","jurisdictionLevel":1},{"id":1705189,"age":39,"year":"1259","julianDay":2180901,"title":"100 Years of Conflict Between England and France Ends","description":"Treaty of Paris was signed on December 4, 1259, which ended 100 years of conflict between England and France.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Treaty_of_Paris_(1259)","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Treaty of Paris 1259","jurisdictionLevel":1},{"id":1705190,"age":70,"year":"1290","julianDay":2192224,"title":"Jews Expelled From England","description":"After years of anti-Semitic behavior, King Edward I expelled Jews from England in 1290.","jurisdictionLevel":1},{"id":1705191,"age":95,"year":"1315","toYear":"1317","julianDay":2201354,"title":"Famine Strikes Europe","description":"A famine caused by cold winters and wet summers across Europe caused m